        <div class="section-title double-line">
            <h2>Disarmament and International <br/> Security Committee</h2>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row orange-50 section-p content">
        <div class="col-lg-12">
            <p>
                The Disarmament and International Security Committee (DISEC), also known as the First Committee, is one of the six main committees of the United Nations General Assembly. It addresses disarmament and international security matters in the light of the general principles of cooperation to the maintenance of international peace and security, in order to prevent the disruption of armed conflict and the heightening of tensions in the international system. Since the past decade, the committee has been focusing on issues of nuclear non-proliferation, small arms illicit traffic and regional militarization.
            </p>
            <p>
                As a subsidiary organ of the General Assembly, the DISEC is entitled to present its recommendations over the issues under its consideration to a plenary meeting of the Assembly, usually in the form of draft resolutions and decisions. Through this mechanism, the First Committee has been the primary origin of legal initiatives that led to important international treaties and conventions, such as the Treaty of Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons of 1968 and the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty of 1996.
            </p>
            <p>
                Each Member State of the United Nations is represented by one delegate in this committee and decisions on draft resolutions and recommendations are approved on a two-thirds majority basis, turning the DISEC into a broad and inclusive platform for the debate of pertinent issues concerning the maintenance of international peace and security.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="row orange section-p content">
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h6>Topic A<br/>Missile Defense Systems</h6>
            <p>
                The Missile Defense Systems are devices that combine anti-aircraft missiles (SAMs), radars, computers and command and control stations, in order to shoot Intercontinental Ballistic Missiles (ICBMs) (MDA 2009; O’Rourke 2013). These systems have been developed and installed in specific locations of the globe, such as in Eastern Europe and East Asia, causing political and strategic impacts in both global and regional levels (Johnson-Freese & Savelsberg 2013; Martins & Cepik 2014). Reportedly, their installation purposes are strictly defensive. However, given their potential and reach, these systems can be also responsible for affecting the capacities of some countries to retaliate against a foreign aggression. This capability, called second-strike capability, is one of exclusivities of the great powers (Cepik 2013). Accordingly, the Missile Shields have a direct connection with the polarity and may be responsible for the change in the international balance and for the climbing crises (Piccolli 2012; Pifer, 2012; Martins & Cepik 2014).
            </p>
            <p>
                In this context, countries’ influence areas are a central element, becoming source of disputes across the globe. The situations are always complex and requires deep reflections by every side. The common scenario is one side claiming that just want to remain sovereign over its territory, while the stronger side insists that, by doing this, the capabilities of the first one are actually jeopardizing its own national security in comparison to a third country. In turn, this third country claims that the systems’ purpose is keeping its own people safe from a fourth country’ weapons. A web of allegations and values holds the tension in high levels, as the polarization. Practical examples of these situations could be seen in in the Eastern Europe, especially the Ukrainian crisis, in Eastern Asia, Korean Peninsula and Japanese-Chinese relations, and in the Persian Gulf with Israel-Iran (Kron 2009; Hildreth & Ek 2011; Piccolli 2012). In spite of been geographically far from each other, they all share the principles stated above, been connected in the high politics level also (Martins & Cepik 2014).
            </p>
            <p>
                In this sense, the international community must address the Missile Defense System’s debate. Questions about the threats to countries’ sovereignty by systems grounded outside its territory, or concerning possible violations of international treaties are central to this debate. The relevance of the topic is not only about its high potential for political instability between the actors of the international system, but also about its practical influence in the conduct of military, economic and social actions in various regions on the globe. Therefore, the Disarmament and International Security committee (DISEC) could be the democratic space in strengthening trust ties between the UN members, and granting more control over future crises’ escalation.
            </p>
