        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h6>Topic B<br/>Prevention Against an<br/> Arms Race in Outer Space</h6>
            <p>
                The importance of space-based technologies can be seen in our everyday life: telecommunications, agriculture, energy, commerce, transportation and innumerous other usages. In a matter of fact, the world is becoming increasingly dependent of space activities and its technologies. This dependence, however, is also the matrix of concerns on the possibility of it becoming a new theatre of war (FAS 2004). Having in mind specific aspects of space, that is, different levels of orbits and the limitation of spatial regions of interest, space can be understood as a new geopolitical level (Klein 2006).
            </p>
            <p>
                Despite the historically known fact that the space age began in 1957, with the launch of Sputnik-1 by the USSR, the national interest in space existed since 1946 (Kali 2012). The arms race in the Cold War was greatly influenced by the new space technologies and activities. Probably, the peak of the arms race in space was the Strategic Defense Initiative (SDI, also known as Star Wars, proposed by U.S. President Ronald Reagan in 1983.  With operations Desert Storm in the Persian Gulf in 1991, Allied Force in Serbia in 1999, Enduring Freedom in Afghanistan in 2001 and Iraqi Freedom in 2003, a new way of making war was empowered by a space-enabled global reconnaissance, precision-strike complex (Hays 2007). Since 2000, approximately 70% of all satellites in space are used for military purposes, such as communication, detection, surveillance, and tracking (Dunningan 2003). Space portrays an important part in wars, and therefore in every countries strategies, of this new century.
            </p>
            <p>
                Having acknowledged the importance of space for countries like the United States and Russia, it should be noted that space activities in the twenty-first century will not be limited only by them. In January 2007 China made a test and launched a missile that successfully destroyed one of its aging weather satellites (New York Times 2007). The increasingly efforts of countries like China, India, South Korea, Israel and Brazil to create its own space complex activities shows a world where multiple interest will be laid on outer space. But with many increasing, and possibly diverging interests, the States may face a militarization of this process, creating a difficult scenario for space stabilization.
            </p>
            <p>
                The strategic importance of space has been shown that it will be played a major role in this century. Nonetheless, the agreements and treaties about this subject are still very limited, impeding an equitable use of space by international law. The first and most commonly known is the 1967 Outer Space Treaty, formally known as the Treaty on Principles Governing the Activities of States in the Exploration and Use of Outer Space, Including the Moon and Other Celestial Bodies. This treaty prohibits nuclear and other weapons of mass destruction from space. However, the 1967 Treaty is outdated and the most recent resolution related to this subject passed more than 13 years ago (Klein 2006). Treaties or agreements about what are space weapons or about a clear definition of outer space do not exist, creating an ambiguous scenario in the current space expansion: if microsatellites can be used against another country´s space asset, should they be considered for potential military use? Can a country´s emerging space program be considered a possible military act? Who should enforce the demilitarization of space and regulate the strategic uses of every country in the different types of orbits, the Security Council?
            </p>
            <p>
                In this simulation, delegations, facing the potential uses of space, will discuss about its strategic and military use, aiming to create guidelines about the demilitarization of space and its peaceful uses. To do so, definitions about the militarization and weaponization of space will have to be laid on the discussion table, in order to reach an understanding of such a ponderous topic. The debate taking place in this committee will question the current strategic use of space and forge a new framework to prevent an arms race in outer space.
            </p>
